								<!-- bodycontent -->
				<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>At boot time, a SPARC system will load the OpenBoot firmware, which then initializes basic hardware (such as the framebuffer, serial ports, keyboard, and disks), tests system functioning, and, optionally, (if the auto-boot? option is set to true) loads a primary bootloader in some way. Otherwise, it gives the user an "ok" prompt, at which to type initialization commands or FORTH instructions. 
</p><p>In theory, one could load an operating system from any device they wish, regardless of whether the device is directly supported by OpenBoot (eg, by typing in FORTH words to stick the raw bytes of the operating system code in memory). In practice, however, an operating system is generally loaded from the hard disk, a floppy, or the network.
</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc"><tr><td><div id="toctitle"><h2>Contents</h2></div>
<ul>
